# Abies grandis

## Grand fir

![Natural range of Abies grandis](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Abies_grandis_range.svg/300px-Abies_grandis_range.svg.png)
Natural range of [Abies grandis](/Abies_grandis)
green - [A. grandis ssp. grandis](/Abies_grandis)
blue - [A. grandis ssp. idahoensis](/Abies_grandis)

Sometimes, even the mundane deserves a closer look, if only to understand the sheer persistence of existence. Take, for instance, *[Abies grandis](/Abies_grandis)* – commonly known as the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis), though it answers to a surprising number of equally uninspired aliases: [giant fir](/Abies_grandis), [lowland white fir](/Abies_grandis), [great silver fir](/Abies_grandis), [western white fir](/Abies_grandis), [Vancouver fir](/Abies_grandis), or even just [Oregon fir](/Abies_grandis). This particular species of [fir](/Fir) is a ubiquitous inhabitant of northwestern [North America](/North_America), apparently quite content to grow anywhere from sea level up to a rather respectable 1,700 metres (5,600 ft) in altitude. It’s not just a casual observer in its environment; it’s a significant, if somewhat unpretentious, component of the [Grand Fir/Douglas Fir Ecoregion](/Ecology_of_the_North_Cascades) that stretches across the [Cascade Range](/Cascade_Range).

These trees don't just exist; they aspire, often reaching heights of 40–70 m (130–230 ft). Indeed, the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) holds the rather specific distinction of potentially being the tallest *[Abies](/Abies)* species on the planet, a fact that probably means more to botanists than to the trees themselves. There are, predictably, two distinct [varieties](/Variety_(botany)) of this species, each adapted to its particular slice of the world: the taller, more robust [coast grand fir](/Abies_grandis), which thrives west of the [Cascade Mountains](/Cascade_Range), and the somewhat shorter, more resilient [interior grand fir](/Abies_grandis), found to the east of those same mountains. Its formal introduction to the scientific community came in 1831, courtesy of [David Douglas](/David_Douglas_(botanist)), who apparently had a knack for finding things.

It shares a notable kinship with the [white fir](/White_fir), a familial connection that hints at shared evolutionary paths and, no doubt, similar ecological squabbles. Historically, the [bark](/Bark_(botany)) of the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) was attributed with various medicinal properties, a testament to humanity’s enduring habit of seeking remedies in nature. In a rather less profound application, it has found popularity in the [United States](/United_States) as a [Christmas tree](/Christmas_tree), an annual ritual of temporary adornment. Its [lumber](/Lumber) is categorized as a [softwood](/Softwood) and is frequently harvested under the collective industrial designation of "hem fir." Beyond its festive, if brief, holiday career, the wood is industrially valuable, used in [paper-making](/Paper) and in construction for purposes such as [framing](/Framing_(construction)) and flooring. Its specific appeal in these applications stems from its notable resistance to both splitting and splintering, a practical quality in a world that often demands durability.

## Conservation status

*   **[Least Concern](/Least_Concern)** ([IUCN 3.1](/IUCN_Red_List)) [\[1\]](/Abies_grandis#References) – A designation that suggests, for now, its continued existence isn't keeping anyone up at night.
*   **Secure** ([NatureServe](/NatureServe_conservation_status)) [\[2\]](/Abies_grandis#References) – Another vote of confidence, indicating it's not currently teetering on the brink.

