## Description

![The bottom (left) and top (right) of the foliage](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Abies_grandis_foliage.jpg/220px-Abies_grandis_foliage.jpg)
The bottom (left) and top (right) of the foliage

The [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) (*[Abies grandis](/Abies_grandis)*) presents itself as a substantial [evergreen](/Evergreen) [conifer](/Conifer), typically achieving heights of 40–70 metres (130–230 feet), though some exceptional specimens have been known to stretch towards a truly impressive 100 m (330 ft). Its [trunk](/Trunk_(botany)) can swell to a diameter of up to 2 m (6+1⁄2 ft), a testament to centuries of slow, deliberate growth. A peculiar characteristic, perhaps a final act of defiance, is that the dead tree tops sometimes fork into new growth, a sort of botanical resurrection. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) The [bark](/Bark_(botany)), which can be as thick as 5 centimetres (2 inches), ranges in color from a reddish hue to a muted gray on the exterior, though a rather unexpected purple can be found within. It is deeply furrowed and segmented into slender plates, a textured skin that speaks of age and resilience. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References)

Its [leaves](/Leaves) are distinctively needle-like and flattened, measuring approximately 3–6 cm (1+1⁄8–2+3⁄8 in) in length and a mere 2 millimetres (3⁄32 in) wide by 0.5 mm thick. The upper surface exhibits a glossy dark green, a visual sheen that belies its stoic nature. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) Beneath, however, lie two distinct green-white bands of [stomata](/Stoma), the tiny pores essential for respiration, and the tip is often subtly notched. While the arrangement of these leaves is technically spiral along the shoot, each individual leaf is variably twisted at its base. This clever adaptation ensures that they all lie in two more-or-less flat ranks on either side of the shoot, creating a remarkably uniform and almost feather-like appearance. The prominent green-white bands of stomata on the lower leaf surface are quite noticeable, almost like subtle stripes. The variable twisting at the base of each leaf is a testament to the tree's efficient use of space, ensuring the leaves are nearly [coplanar](/Coplanar) and maximize light absorption.

### Cones

The reproductive structures, the [cones](/Conifer_cone), begin as a verdant green before maturing into a reddish-brown. They are somewhat substantial, typically measuring 6–12 cm (2+1⁄4–4+3⁄4 in) long [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) and 3.5–4.5 cm (1+1⁄2–1+3⁄4 in) broad. Each cone is composed of approximately 100–150 scales, with the scale bracts remaining short and discreetly hidden within the closed cone. The winged [seeds](/Seed), designed for dispersal by wind, are liberated when the cones, having fulfilled their purpose, disintegrate upon reaching maturity, typically about six months following pollination. [\[1\]](/Abies_grandis#References)

### Varieties

![Old-growth copse in inland Oregon](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Abies_grandis_Oregon.jpg/220px-Abies_grandis_Oregon.jpg)
[Old-growth](/Old-growth) copse in inland [Oregon](/Oregon)

As previously noted, the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) exhibits two primary [varieties](/Variety_(botany)). While currently classified as varieties, it’s arguably more accurate, and certainly more logical, to consider them at the [subspecies](/Subspecies) rank, though the botanical establishment has yet to formally make this distinction.

*   ***Abies grandis var. grandis***: This is the **Coast grand fir**. It is found predominantly in coastal lowland forests, thriving at elevations ranging from sea level up to 900 m. Its geographic reach extends from [Vancouver Island](/Vancouver_Island) and the coastal regions of [British Columbia](/British_Columbia), stretching southward into [Sonoma County, California](/Sonoma_County,_California). This particular variety is characterized by its impressive size and remarkably rapid growth rate, often reaching heights of 70 m. Its foliage is distinctly flattened on all shoots, presenting a uniform appearance. Its cones are typically slightly narrower, generally less than 4 cm broad, and possess thinner, rather flexible scales. This coastal variant demonstrates a notable tolerance for winter [temperatures](/Temperature), enduring conditions down to approximately -25° to −30 °C. When growing in favorable conditions, young trees of this variety can achieve growth rates exceeding 1.5 m per year. [\[1\]](/Abies_grandis#References)

*   ***Abies grandis var. idahoensis***: This is the **Interior grand fir**. It inhabits the interior forests at higher altitudes, specifically between (600–) 900–1800 m. Its distribution spans the eastern slope of the [Cascades](/Cascade_Range) in [Washington](/Washington_(state)) and extends into the [Rocky Mountains](/Rocky_Mountains) from southeastern [British Columbia](/British_Columbia) south to central [Idaho](/Idaho), northeastern [Oregon](/Oregon), and western [Montana](/Montana). In contrast to its coastal cousin, this variety is generally smaller and exhibits a slower growth rate, typically reaching heights of 40–45 m. Its foliage is not uniformly flattened across all shoots; instead, the leaves often rise above the shoot, a trait particularly noticeable on the upper crown shoots. The cones of this variety are slightly stouter, mostly exceeding 4 cm broad, and are characterized by thicker, somewhat woody scales. The interior [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) is remarkably cold-hardy, capable of tolerating winter temperatures as low as −40 °C. Even under optimal growing conditions, its annual growth rate rarely surpasses 0.6 m when young. [\[1\]](/Abies_grandis#References)

The [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) maintains a very close genetic and morphological relationship with the [white fir](/White_fir) (*[Abies concolor](/Abies_concolor)*). This genetic proximity is particularly evident in central [Oregon](/Oregon), where the two species frequently intergrade, blurring the lines of distinct classification. Firs found in the [Blue Mountains](/Blue_Mountains_(Pacific_Northwest)) and on the [East Cascade Slope](/Eastern_Cascades_Slopes_and_Foothills) of [Oregon](/Oregon) often display characteristics intermediate between the two species, both in their genetic makeup and their outward appearance. These intergrades are commonly referred to as "*[Abies grandis](/Abies_grandis) x [concolor](/Abies_concolor)*," a hybrid form that itself gradually transitions into *[Abies concolor lowiana](/Abies_concolor)* further south, particularly as one approaches the California state line. [\[5\]](/Abies_grandis#References)[\[6\]](/Abies_grandis#References)[\[7\]](/Abies_grandis#References) It seems even trees find ways to complicate taxonomy.

## Taxonomy

The species was initially documented and described by the Scottish botanical explorer [David Douglas](/David_Douglas_(botanist)). In 1830, he embarked on the arduous task of transporting its [seeds](/Seed) back to [Britain](/United_Kingdom), effectively introducing it to European horticulture. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) The following year, in 1831, Douglas provided a formal description of the specimens he had meticulously collected along the majestic [Columbia River](/Columbia_River) in the geographically diverse [Pacific Northwest](/Pacific_Northwest). [\[3\]](/Abies_grandis#References) One can only imagine the sheer tenacity required for such an endeavor, all for the sake of cataloging another tree.

## Distribution and habitat

The coastal [variety](/Variety_(botany)) of [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) thrives within the lush confines of temperate rainforest environments, stretching along the [Pacific coast](/Pacific_Ocean) from the southwestern reaches of [British Columbia](/British_Columbia) down to [Northern California](/Northern_California). Meanwhile, its inland counterpart prefers the more rigorous montane [conifer](/Conifer) forests of eastern [Washington](/Washington_(state)), the [Idaho Panhandle](/Idaho_Panhandle), and the far western fringes of [Montana](/Montana). This species can be found growing at elevations that climb as high as 1,700 m (5,600 ft), demonstrating a remarkable adaptability to varying altitudes. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References)

These habitats are typically characterized by receiving a minimum of 640 mm (25 in) of annual rainfall. Despite this seemingly adequate precipitation, these areas are often still considered too dry, or perhaps simply fall outside the optimal range, for more [shade-tolerant](/Shade-tolerant) botanical competitors such as the [western hemlock](/Western_hemlock) and [western redcedar](/Western_redcedar). [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) Interestingly, alongside its close relative, the [white fir](/White_fir), the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) exhibits a greater degree of [shade tolerance](/Shade-tolerant) than the ubiquitous [Douglas-fir](/Douglas-fir). [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) A subtle advantage in the perpetual arboreal struggle for light.

## Ecology

In what can only be described as an unintended consequence of human intervention, specifically [wildfire suppression](/Wildfire_suppression) efforts, the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) has managed to proliferate significantly in areas that were historically dominated by other, more [fire-resistant](/Fire_ecology) species. These included the inland [Douglas fir](/Douglas-fir), the stately [ponderosa pine](/Ponderosa_pine), and the resilient [western larch](/Western_larch). [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) This ecological shift, however, comes with its own set of problems. The absence of smaller, more frequent fires allows both [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) and [white fir](/White_fir) saplings to grow unchecked, forming what is known as a "[fuel ladder](/Fuel_ladder)." This ladder effectively provides a pathway for flames to climb from the forest floor directly into the canopy, thereby enabling devastating [crown fires](/Crown_fire). [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) It seems even trying to help can make things worse.

Furthermore, the [grand fir's](/Abies_grandis) [bark](/Bark_(botany)) is comparatively thinner than that of the [white fir](/White_fir), rendering it more vulnerable to various threats, including the very fires it now inadvertently fuels, as well as rot. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) While specimens have historically been recorded living for nearly 300 years, the current environmental stressors mean that a lifespan of 100 years is now far more typical. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References)

The tree is also perpetually besieged by a variety of defoliating insects. A particularly notable example occurred in the late 20th century, when epidemics of the [western spruce budworm](/Western_spruce_budworm) decimated significant populations of [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) in both the eastern [Cascades](/Cascade_Range) and the [Blue Mountains](/Blue_Mountains_(Pacific_Northwest)). [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) Another critical vulnerability stems from its inability to effectively utilize [pitch](/Pitch_(resin)) to seal wounds. This deficiency, whether from [logging](/Logging) damage or minor fires, creates an open invitation for various rot fungi, which exploit these weaknesses with predictable efficiency. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) East of the [Cascade ridge](/Cascade_Range), a common affliction sees [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) trunks infected by the [Indian paint fungus](/Echinodontium_tinctorium), an unmistakable indicator of a rotten core. Such compromised specimens are often prone to becoming waterlogged, leading to catastrophic splitting during freezing weather. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References)

Despite its vulnerabilities, the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) does play a role in the local ecosystem. [Pileated woodpeckers](/Pileated_woodpecker) are known to actively forage on both [grand](/Abies_grandis) and [white firs](/White_fir), seeking out insects and suitable locations for nesting. The rotten cores, while detrimental to the tree, inadvertently create valuable shelters and dens for a variety of animals, including the formidable [black bears](/American_black_bear). [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) A small consolation, perhaps, for a tree perpetually under siege.

## Uses

In a rudimentary application of its natural form, the dense boughs of the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) can provide surprisingly effective rain shelter for humans. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) A primitive, yet undeniably practical, use.

Historically, [Native American](/Indigenous_peoples_of_North_America) tribes utilized both the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) and the [white fir](/White_fir) for a range of medicinal and practical purposes. The [bark](/Bark_(botany)) or [pitch](/Pitch_(resin)) was often powdered and employed in traditional treatments for ailments such as [tuberculosis](/Tuberculosis) or various skin conditions. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) Specifically, the [Nlaka'pamux](/Nlaka%27pamux) people ingeniously used the [bark](/Bark_(botany)) as a durable covering for their lodges and even in the construction of canoes, while branches provided comfortable bedding. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) The inner [bark](/Bark_(botany)) of the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) was particularly valued by some [Plateau Indian](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Northwest_Plateau) tribes for its purported efficacy in treating common [colds](/Colds) and [fever](/Fever). [\[8\]](/Abies_grandis#References) The [Okanagan-Colville tribe](/Okanagan_people) even harnessed the species for its perceived properties as a strengthening drug, believed to counteract feelings of weakness. [\[9\]](/Abies_grandis#References)

Beyond its practical applications, the foliage of the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) emits an appealing [citrus](/Citrus)-like scent, a pleasant aroma that has made it a popular choice for [Christmas decorations](/Christmas_decorations) in the [United States](/United_States), including, rather predictably, [Christmas trees](/Christmas_tree). However, its rather stiff branches pose a logistical challenge, making it uneconomical to pack efficiently for commercial distribution. [\[4\]](/Abies_grandis#References) It also finds a place as an ornamental tree, gracing the landscapes of large parks with its stately presence. It seems even trees are subject to seasonal trends and aesthetic judgments.

## Timber

![Trunk cross-section](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Abies_grandis_cross_section_UBC_BG.jpg/220px-Abies_grandis_cross_section_UBC_BG.jpg)
Trunk cross-section

The [lumber](/Lumber) derived from the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) is characterized by its non-resinous nature and fine texture. [\[3\]](/Abies_grandis#References) In the convoluted world of the North American [logging](/Logging) industry, the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) is often grouped under the rather generic moniker "hem fir." This term encompasses a collection of species whose wood is considered interchangeable in terms of its properties and applications. Specifically, this group includes the [California red fir](/Abies_magnifica), [noble fir](/Noble_fir), [Pacific silver fir](/Pacific_silver_fir), [white fir](/White_fir), and [western hemlock](/Western_hemlock). Consequently, [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) timber is frequently shipped alongside these other species, blurring its individual identity in the market. It can also be simply referred to as "white fir" lumber, an even broader umbrella term that also covers *[Abies amabilis](/Abies_amabilis)*, *[Abies concolor](/Abies_concolor)*, and *[Abies magnifica](/Abies_magnifica)*. Such are the indignities of commodification.

As a "hem fir," the [lumber](/Lumber) from the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis) is classified as a [softwood](/Softwood). Its primary applications include [paper](/Paper) making, the fabrication of packing crates, and various construction purposes. "Hem fir" is a frequent choice for [framing](/Framing_(construction)) in construction, largely due to its ability to consistently meet the [building code](/Building_code) [span requirements](/Span_(architecture)) across a multitude of construction projects. [\[10\]](/Abies_grandis#References)

Within the hierarchy of North American construction materials, the [trunk](/Trunk_(botany)) of the [grand fir](/Abies_grandis), as a "hem fir," is considered to possess strength properties slightly inferior to the "Douglas fir-[larch](/Larch)" species combination. However, it is demonstrably stronger than the "Douglas fir-South" and "spruce-pine-fir (South)" species combinations – both of which are, again, umbrella terms for various species with comparable wood characteristics. Because its strength closely approximates that of the [Douglas fir-larch](/Douglas-fir-larch) group, it routinely satisfies the structural [load-bearing](/Load-bearing_wall) requirements for [framing](/Framing_(construction)) in residential, light commercial, and heavy construction applications. When excluding the [Douglas fir-larch](/Douglas-fir-larch) combination, "hem fir's" [modulus of elasticity](/Modulus_of_elasticity) (MOE or E), which serves as a critical stiffness factor in floor systems, surpasses that of all other western species combinations. Furthermore, "hem fir" is often favored by builders for its commendable ability to securely hold nails and screws without splitting, and its notably low propensity for splintering when sawed. [\[10\]](/Abies_grandis#References) Practicality, it seems, often triumphs over individual distinction.

## Notable specimens

In February 2022, a particularly ambitious [coast grand fir](/Abies_grandis) growing south of [Bergen](/Bergen), [Norway](/Norway), was officially identified as [Norway's](/Norway) tallest tree. It measured an impressive 53.7 m (176 ft). [\[11\]](/Abies_grandis#References) One can only assume it was quite pleased with itself.